= About Typst

Typst is a new, more modern and easy to learn (but powerful) typesetting language much like LaTeX (except a lot better) @Typst. It has an easy to read documentation @TypstDocumentation and is compatible with BibTeX for easy citation like @TypstCite. It also has support for packages like Zap @TypstZap which is used to draw electrical circuits like @electrical-circuit. Also it is blazing fast, this compile only took $90 m s$! It works online (much like Overleaf) but you can also download the compiler to your computer, everything is open source!

#quote(attribution: [ChatGPT], block: true, quotes: true)[
Typst is a modern typesetting system designed to combine the power of LaTeX with the usability of Markdown. It offers a clean, concise syntax that is easy to read and write, making it particularly appealing to users who find LaTeX overly complex or verbose. Typst was created with a strong focus on productivity, enabling users to write and style documents quickly without sacrificing typographic quality.

One of Typst’s standout features is its real-time preview and fast compilation, which significantly reduces iteration time. Unlike LaTeX, which often requires external tools and packages for advanced formatting, Typst comes with many built-in capabilities such as references, equations, custom layouts, and scripting. This makes it especially useful for technical documents, academic papers, and reports.

Typst also emphasizes consistency and reusability through its template and function system. Users can define reusable components and apply styles programmatically, much like in modern programming languages. The language itself is Turing complete, allowing advanced customization when needed.

Overall, Typst provides a compelling alternative to traditional typesetting tools by offering a balance between ease of use and expressive power, making it suitable for both casual and professional document creation. It’s open-source and rapidly evolving with community input and support.
